00:02:20,173 --> 00:02:25,740
You know [nǐ] and [wǒ] on the list.

19
00:02:25,740 --> 00:02:28,821
what about [de] here?

20
00:02:28,821 --> 00:02:33,819
[de] is the most frequently used character
in Chinese.

21
00:02:33,819 --> 00:02:37,210
It has different functions, but

22
00:02:37,210 --> 00:02:41,780
here [de] is used to mark possession.

23
00:02:41,780 --> 00:02:46,793
One way to think about [de] is that

24
00:02:46,793 --> 00:02:52,299
it works like 's in English.

25
00:02:52,299 --> 00:02:56,145
So [wǒ de] means my/mine,

26
00:02:56,145 --> 00:03:01,920
[nǐ de] means your, yours.

27
00:03:01,920 --> 00:03:06,578
How do you say his or her then?

28
00:03:06,578 --> 00:03:13,905
Yes, it's [tā de].

29
00:03:13,905 --> 00:03:19,905
The structure is here: noun,

30
00:03:19,905 --> 00:03:26,910
or pronoun plus [de] plus noun.

31
00:03:26,910 --> 00:03:33,019
[wǒ de diànhuà], my phone.

32
00:03:33,019 --> 00:03:38,703
[tā de māma], his mother.

33
00:03:38,703 --> 00:03:48,495
[māma de míngzi], mother's name.

34
00:03:48,495 --> 00:03:53,366
[duōshao] is how much or how many.

35
00:03:53,366 --> 00:03:58,915
It's used to ask about numbers,
prices etc.

36
00:03:58,915 --> 00:04:09,604
For example, [Zhè ge duōshao qián?]
[Zhè ge duōshao qián?]

