46
00:05:09,628 --> 00:05:19,919
[liùèrqīwǔ sìyāoèrèr]

47
00:05:19,919 --> 00:05:25,307
[Xùdōng de diànhuà hàomǎ.]

48
00:05:25,307 --> 00:05:35,744
[liùèrqīliù qīyāoqīwǔ]

49
00:05:35,744 --> 00:05:41,783
You may have noticed that Tingna and
Xudong didn't say [yī],

50
00:05:41,783 --> 00:05:46,065
but they said [yāo] for
their telephone numbers.

51
00:05:47,551 --> 00:05:49,553
Why?

52
00:05:49,553 --> 00:05:54,929
In speaking, when you tell
numbers if there is [yī],

53
00:05:54,929 --> 00:05:57,957
you could say [yāo] instead.

54
00:05:57,957 --> 00:06:03,510
That is because the pronunciation of [yī(1)]
and [qī(7)] are quite similar.

55
00:06:04,960 --> 00:06:10,745
So, to distinguish them,
you can change [yī] to [yāo].

56
00:06:10,745 --> 00:06:23,493
For example, emergency number in China,
[yāo yāo línɡ].

57
00:06:23,493 --> 00:06:31,439
And in America, [jiǔ yāo yāo (911)].

58
00:06:31,439 --> 00:06:37,304
Okay, do you remember the last
sentence in the video,

59
00:06:37,304 --> 00:06:49,404
